WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:16.720
Let's talk about the provisioning life cycle.

00:16.720 --> 00:34.760
The provisioning life cycle is all about how an organization, provisions, or...

00:34.760 --> 00:36.800
Let's talk about the provisioning life cycle.

00:36.800 --> 00:41.080
The provisioning life cycle is all about how an organization, provisions, or creates

00:41.080 --> 00:42.480
new user accounts.

00:42.480 --> 00:47.280
How those accounts, those users, are managed throughout their entire life cycle, their

00:47.280 --> 00:51.800
entire time at the company, and then how finally those accounts are removed.

00:51.800 --> 00:55.080
So when you hear about the provisioning life cycle, a three major pieces are typically

00:55.080 --> 00:59.520
your provisioning, your review, and your revocation.

00:59.520 --> 01:02.000
Let's talk about the first step of the provisioning life cycle.

01:02.000 --> 01:05.160
This is where the organization will create a new account.

01:05.160 --> 01:09.440
And that includes things like doing backgrounds checks and making sure that the employee has

01:09.440 --> 01:15.880
the right skills for the job, and it also includes actually creating the account.

01:15.880 --> 01:18.760
And as part of that, you should do something known as identity proofing, which means

01:18.760 --> 01:22.600
that you're making sure the employee is who they say they are by checking passports

01:22.600 --> 01:24.680
or driver's license or something like that.

01:24.680 --> 01:27.640
And then finally, creating the actual account.

01:27.640 --> 01:31.560
But the account should be created only with the principles of least privilege you need

01:31.560 --> 01:32.560
to know.

01:32.560 --> 01:34.680
In other words, their access has to be approved.

01:34.680 --> 01:36.600
And who should be approving that access?

01:36.600 --> 01:37.600
The owner.

01:37.840 --> 01:42.840
Now, once a user has accounts or a number of accounts within the organization, the next

01:42.840 --> 01:47.560
step of the provisioning life cycle is reviewing those accounts.

01:47.560 --> 01:52.240
And review means that the owner or the system owner of the account should be reviewing that

01:52.240 --> 01:55.000
account to make sure the access remains appropriate.

01:55.000 --> 01:58.760
The final step of the provisioning life cycle is revocation.

01:58.760 --> 02:01.760
And revocation actually includes two important parts.

02:01.760 --> 02:05.560
Part of it might be if someone changes roles within the organization, you actually have

02:05.560 --> 02:11.320
to not only grant them new access, but remove any existing access that they no longer need.

02:11.320 --> 02:16.920
And revocation also includes when you finally get to leave the company, when you're dead

02:16.920 --> 02:20.640
and you can't help anymore or you can't do any more good work, no, I mean revocation

02:20.640 --> 02:25.080
is when you leave the company and your access needs to be removed.

02:25.080 --> 02:26.920
And so that's the entire provisioning life cycle.

02:26.920 --> 02:29.600
And let's just dig into a couple little pieces.

02:29.600 --> 02:35.240
So when it comes to user access reviews, how often should they be conducted?

02:35.240 --> 02:36.880
Who should be conducting the review?

02:36.880 --> 02:38.800
Which accounts should be reviewed most often?

02:38.800 --> 02:41.440
All of this falls under the review process.

02:41.440 --> 02:45.680
And the perfect answer for who should be reviewing access to make sure that that access

02:45.680 --> 02:52.000
is appropriate, the owners, owners of systems, of applications are the ones that should be

02:52.000 --> 02:56.080
reviewing to make sure the access is appropriate.

02:56.080 --> 02:59.840
And if you got a question asking you how often should access be reviewed or if you're

02:59.840 --> 03:04.600
thinking about something like this, the incorrect answer is any specific time like once

03:04.600 --> 03:07.760
a year or once a month or once every week.

03:07.760 --> 03:12.600
The perfect answer is in fact actually as often as necessary based on the value of the

03:12.600 --> 03:13.600
system.

03:13.600 --> 03:14.880
Why is that the perfect answer?

03:14.880 --> 03:19.960
Well, because different systems have different value to the organization, different risk profiles.

03:19.960 --> 03:24.880
And so their users need to be reviewed at different frequencies, different cycles, different

03:24.880 --> 03:26.200
cadences.

03:26.200 --> 03:30.480
And so for a very high value system where there might be a lot of turnover in users, maybe

03:30.480 --> 03:32.360
weekly reviews are appropriate.

03:32.360 --> 03:36.480
For lower battery systems with less turnover, maybe once a month, maybe even once a year

03:36.480 --> 03:37.480
is appropriate.

03:37.480 --> 03:42.040
So the perfect answer is as often as necessary.

03:42.040 --> 03:45.520
And which type of accounts should be reviewed most often?

03:45.520 --> 03:47.720
I'll let you know the answer to this one.

03:47.720 --> 03:52.080
High value accounts, system accounts, root accounts, those are the accounts that we want

03:52.080 --> 03:53.440
to review most often.

04:00.480 --> 04:07.480
And so for a very high value system with less turnover, maybe even once a year or once a year

04:07.480 --> 04:10.480
or once a year or once a year or once a year or once a year or once a year or once a year.

